"""
context layer: Joshua 6–8.
Ch 6 (27 v): Jericho siege and cherem.
Ch 7 (26 v): Achan's sin and Valley of Achor.
Ch 8 (35 v): Ai taken; Ebal covenant ceremony.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
  "6": {
    "1": "<p>Jericho is identified with Tell es-Sultan, a mound at the spring of Ain es-Sultan in the Jordan Valley just north of the Dead Sea. It is one of the oldest continuously occupied sites in the world, with occupation layers going back to the Neolithic (ca. 9000 BCE). The archaeological debate about the Late Bronze Age city is significant: John Garstang (excavated 1930–1936) identified a destruction layer (City IV, his &ldquo;City D&rdquo;) with a collapsed outer wall dated to ca. 1400 BCE, consistent with the early exodus date (1446 BCE). Kathleen Kenyon (1952–1958) re-examined the site and argued the LBA destruction Garstang found was actually MB IIC (ca. 1550 BCE), with no significant LBA occupation present — creating the apparent archaeological problem that there was no city to conquer in the late LBA. More recent analysis (Bryant Wood, 1990) re-dates Kenyon's City IV destruction back to ca. 1400 BCE using carbon-14 and ceramic evidence, reopening the debate. The scarcity of Late Bronze remains at Tell es-Sultan may reflect Jericho's status as a small, lightly occupied administrative post rather than a major fortified city — consistent with the narrative's emphasis on the walls as the only military feature.</p>",
    "2": "<p>YHWH's opening assurance — &ldquo;See, I have given Jericho into your hand&rdquo; — uses the prophetic perfect (the future act stated as already accomplished from the divine perspective), a standard feature of holy-war rhetoric in which YHWH's prior gift of victory precedes the human act of taking it. The same formula appears in Deuteronomy's conquest speeches (Deut 2:24; 7:2; 20:13) and reflects a theological claim: Israel is not conquering Canaan by military superiority but executing a divine decree already enacted in the heavenly realm. The ANE parallel is the Assyrian and Hittite royal annals, where the storm-god gives the king his enemies before the battle — but the Israelite version differs in that there is no elaborate ritual to secure the god's favor; the gift is unconditional and prior.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The seven-day march with seven priests carrying seven rams&rsquo; horn trumpets (<em>shofar hayovel</em>) has the structure of a liturgical procession rather than a military siege. The <em>hayovel</em> (Jubilee horn) directly connects to Leviticus 25: the Jubilee year was announced by the blowing of the <em>shofar hayovel</em> on the Day of Atonement, releasing all debt-slaves and restoring all ancestral land. Jericho, as the first city taken, functions as the &ldquo;Jubilee city&rdquo; — its conquest inaugurates the land redistribution to Israel's tribes. The seven-fold structure (seven days, seven priests, seven trumpets, seventh day seven times) is patterned on creation-week: the completion of the conquest, like the completion of creation, is on the seventh. The number seven also signals holy completeness — the city falls not through human engineering but through divine decree at the appointed fullness of time.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The ark of the covenant's placement at the center of the procession signals that it is YHWH's march, not Joshua's. In the wilderness narratives, the ark led Israel's movements (Num 10:33-36); at the Jordan crossing the ark went ahead of the people (Josh 3:6). The procession's order — armed men in front, priests with trumpets, ark, rear guard — mirrors the arrangement of the tabernacle camp (Num 2) and the wilderness march, suggesting that the conquest is a continuation of the wilderness journey, not a departure from it. The ark's presence transforms the military action into a liturgical act: YHWH is coming to take possession of his land, and Israel is his processional retinue.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The command to shout (<em>rua</em>) when the trumpets blast is a technical term in holy war: <em>teru'ah</em> is the battle cry and the blast of the ram's horn simultaneously. In Leviticus 23:24 the same term marks the Feast of Trumpets (Rosh Hashanah), suggesting an overlap between the cultic calendar and the conquest narrative. In Numbers 23:21, Balaam observes &ldquo;the shout of a king is among them&rdquo; (<em>teru'at melek</em>) — YHWH's presence with Israel expressed through the battle shout. The collapse of the walls at the <em>teru'ah</em> is the narrative's way of saying: the conquest was YHWH's direct act, not Israel's military achievement, and the mechanism was the presence of the divine king in his processional ark.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The seven rams&rsquo; horn trumpets (<em>shivah shofarot hayovelim</em>) are specifically Jubilee instruments. The LXX renders <em>hayovel</em> as <em>salpigges</em> (trumpets), losing the Jubilee connection, but the Hebrew is precise. The <em>shofar hayovel</em> was the instrument of release, restoration, and liberty — its use in the conquest of Jericho signals that Israel is entering their inheritance, not merely taking territory. The priests are not soldiers; their role is to carry the instruments of divine declaration. The military men in front and behind are essentially a liturgical escort for the real agent of the siege: the divine presence in the ark, declared by the Jubilee trumpets.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The instruction &ldquo;do not shout, let no word come out of your mouth&rdquo; for the first six days creates a sustained liturgical silence. This is the silence before the divine act — the same silence commanded before holy-war encounters (Exod 14:14: &ldquo;YHWH will fight for you; you need only be still&rdquo;). The silence emphasizes that Israel's part is not military action but disciplined participation in YHWH's procession. The contrast with the shout on day seven is deliberate: six days of silence followed by one commanded shout mirrors the creation week structure and heightens the theological point that the seventh day is the day of divine completion.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Joshua's command to the people on day one — march, do not shout, do not speak — positions the conquest as an act of liturgical discipline. Military discipline and cultic discipline are identical in the holy-war framework. The Israelites are a holy army precisely because they are YHWH's processional retinue; their discipline is the discipline of approaching the divine presence, not merely the discipline of a well-ordered military force. This theological framing of the army as a liturgical procession is unique to Israel in the ANE and reflects the covenant conception of war as enacted worship.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The arrangement of the procession — armed vanguard, priests with trumpets, ark, armed rear guard — reflects both military and liturgical order. The Hebrew term for the rear guard (<em>measef</em>) means &ldquo;gatherer&rdquo; or &ldquo;rear assembly,&rdquo; used also in Isaiah 52:12: &ldquo;YHWH will go before you, and the God of Israel will be your rear guard.&rdquo; The procession around Jericho is thus a miniature of the exodus journey: divine presence leading, divine presence protecting from behind, the people in the middle walking in covenant order.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The silence command is reinforced here: &ldquo;you shall not shout or make your voice heard, neither shall any word go out of your mouth.&rdquo; The phrase &ldquo;no word go out of your mouth&rdquo; is the antithesis of the <em>teru'ah</em> to come — all speech is reserved for the commanded moment. This restraint on human speech parallels the restraint on human military initiative: YHWH alone acts, Israel alone obeys. The liturgical silence is the form of their obedience.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The ark of YHWH goes around the city once — the beginning of the seven-day circuit. The circuit is not a military inspection but a territorial claim: YHWH walking the perimeter of the city he is claiming. In ANE boundary-walking rituals, deities or kings walked the boundaries of territory to assert ownership (cf. the treaty texts from Ugarit and the Hittite archives where divine-witness tours established territorial grants). YHWH's circuit of Jericho is the assertion of his sovereign claim before the visible judgment falls.</p>",
    "12": "<p>On the second day they rose early — the same verb (<em>hashkem</em>) used of Abraham rising early to go to Moriah (Gen 22:3) and of Moses rising early at Sinai (Exod 34:4). The early rising signals eager obedience; the holy-war context makes each early rising a recommitment to the task. The repetition through seven days also structures the narrative as a week, with each day building liturgical pressure toward the seventh.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The seven priests, seven trumpets, ark, and procession repeat exactly — the narrative deliberately slows down to emphasize the daily repetition. Biblical scholars note the &ldquo;repetitive resumption&rdquo; (Wiederaufnahme) technique here: the repetition is not literary redundancy but a narrative device signaling covenantal regularity. Each circuit is a liturgical enactment of the same divine claim; the repetition is the form of Israel's obedience and YHWH's patient assertion.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Six days of single circuits establish the pattern. The number six signals incompleteness in the biblical symbolic system — six days of creation work before the seventh-day rest. The six circuits achieve nothing visible in military terms; their purpose is entirely theological: to establish that the seventh circuit, with its sevenfold intensity, is the divine completion. Jericho does not fall through attrition or military pressure over six days; it falls through divine act on the seventh day at the moment of completion.</p>",
    "15": "<p>On the seventh day they rose early at dawn (<em>ba'alot hashachar</em>) and circled seven times — the only day with seven circuits and the only day with specified dawn timing. The dawn rising connects to the theophanic dawn traditions (Exod 14:24: YHWH in the pillar of fire looked down at dawn and threw Egypt into confusion) and the Passover imagery (Israel left Egypt at night; the Egyptian army was destroyed at dawn). The seventh day of the Jericho siege is structurally analogous to the Passover night: the night of seven circuits followed by the dawn destruction.</p>",
    "16": "<p>On the seventh circuit of the seventh day the priests blow the trumpets and Joshua commands the shout — &ldquo;for YHWH has given you the city.&rdquo; The prophetic perfect from verse 2 is now confirmed: what YHWH declared already accomplished at the beginning is now enacted visibly. The shout (<em>teru'ah</em>) is the human response to the divine declaration, not the cause of the wall's collapse. Theologically, the sequence is: divine decree → human obedience → divine fulfillment, with no human military action in the middle.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The <em>cherem</em> (devoted/banned thing) declared over Jericho is the book's central concept for the first conquered city. <em>Cherem</em> is from a root meaning to separate, set apart, or prohibit; it covers a spectrum from &ldquo;devoted to YHWH's use&rdquo; (the metals going to the sanctuary treasury, v19) to &ldquo;devoted to destruction&rdquo; (everything else). The Mesha Stele (ca. 840 BCE), inscribed by King Mesha of Moab, uses the same term: &ldquo;I devoted it [Israel's garrison at Nebo] to Ashtar-Chemosh,&rdquo; indicating that <em>cherem</em> was an ANE holy-war concept applied to the defeated as a gift to the victorious deity. What distinguishes the Israelite <em>cherem</em> is that it is commanded by YHWH as a theological quarantine — Canaanite religious practice is not to survive to corrupt Israel. Rahab and her household are explicitly excluded from the <em>cherem</em> because she had aligned herself with YHWH's purposes (v25).</p>",
    "18": "<p>The warning against taking anything from the <em>cherem</em> is framed in terms of contamination: &ldquo;lest when you have devoted [<em>cheramtem</em>] it you take any of the devoted things [<em>cherem</em>] and make the camp of Israel a thing devoted [<em>cherem</em>] and bring trouble upon it.&rdquo; The logic is contagion: the <em>cherem</em> status is transferable; if anyone takes <em>cherem</em> items, they become <em>cherem</em> themselves and bring that status onto the whole camp. This is the narrative setup for the Achan episode in chapter 7, where exactly this contamination logic is worked out. The <em>cherem</em> is not merely a military policy but a theological fence maintaining the purity of Israel's covenant relationship.</p>",
    "19": "<p>All silver and gold and vessels of bronze and iron are holy to YHWH and go into his treasury. This is the firstfruits principle applied to the first city: Jericho, as the first conquered city, belongs entirely to YHWH as the firstfruits of the land's produce belong to him. The metals — valuable and durable — go to the sanctuary treasury (the same logic as dedicating the firstfruits of the harvest). Everything else is destroyed. The distinction is between what can be purified and incorporated into YHWH's service (metals can be refined) and what cannot (living things contaminated by Canaanite practice). The sanctuary treasury (in later tradition, the bronze and iron vessels become the foundation of the temple treasury, 1 Kings 7:51) thus contains the firstfruits of the conquest.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The wall collapsed (<em>vatipol hachomah tachtehah</em>) and the people went up straight ahead. No mechanism is described — neither earthquake, mining, nor battering ram. The narrative presents the collapse as the direct result of the shout (and behind the shout, the divine declaration of verse 2). Archaeological note: the walls at Tell es-Sultan show evidence of a catastrophic collapse in the relevant destruction layer — Garstang and Wood describe the outer revetment wall falling outward onto the base, creating a ramped approach of rubble up which attackers could walk. The phrase &ldquo;went up straight ahead&rdquo; is consistent with this: no gate assault, but a broad-front entry over the collapsed debris.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The <em>cherem</em> of all living things (men and women, young and old, ox and sheep and donkey) is stated matter-of-factly. The thoroughness of the command reflects the theological logic of the <em>cherem</em>: partial execution creates the contamination it was meant to prevent (as Saul's partial <em>cherem</em> of the Amalekites in 1 Sam 15 demonstrates, with Samuel's subsequent rebuke). The moral weight of this text has exercised biblical interpreters from Origen (who allegorized it as the soul's conquest of its passions) to modern OT scholars (who situate it in the ANE genre of holy-war rhetoric, noting that Mesha's Moabite Stele makes similar total-destruction claims that archaeology does not confirm literally). The narrative's theological point is not a general warrant for violence but a specific act of divine judgment on cities whose sin had reached the point of no return (Gen 15:16: &ldquo;the iniquity of the Amorites is not yet complete&rdquo;).</p>",
    "22": "<p>Joshua's dispatch of the two spies to bring out Rahab fulfills the oath sworn in chapter 2. The spies had sworn by their lives (<em>nafshotenu tachat motkhem</em>, &ldquo;our lives for yours&rdquo;) — a solemn oath formula that creates a binding obligation. Rahab's rescue is the narrative embodiment of the <em>chesed</em> principle: the loyal love shown to the spies is repaid by loyal love to her household. The inclusion of her &ldquo;father, mother, brothers, and all who belonged to her&rdquo; reflects the household-solidarity principle of covenant: the faith of one head of household can cover the whole family (as Rahab functioned as a de facto household head in sheltering the spies).</p>",
    "23": "<p>The burning of the city and everything in it completes the <em>cherem</em>. Fire is the standard medium of <em>cherem</em> destruction (Deut 13:16 commands burning a city that has gone after other gods). The metals are exempted because fire purifies them rather than destroying them — consistent with the purification logic of Numbers 31:22-23, where metals taken from Midian must pass through fire for purification. The burning of Jericho is the visual enactment of offering the city to YHWH: the smoke ascending is the sacrifice of the first city, the firstfruits offering of the conquest.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Joshua pronounces a rebuilding curse on Jericho: whoever rebuilds it &ldquo;shall lay its foundation at the cost of his firstborn, and at the cost of his youngest shall he set up its gates.&rdquo; This curse is fulfilled literally in 1 Kings 16:34 — Hiel of Bethel rebuilt Jericho in the time of Ahab, &ldquo;he laid its foundation at the cost of Abiram his firstborn, and set up its gates at the cost of his youngest son Segub, according to the word of YHWH that he spoke by Joshua.&rdquo; The curse-fulfillment is one of the clearest examples in Kings of an earlier prophetic word being literally enacted; it also frames the Jericho destruction as permanently significant — the city is to remain a warning monument, not a site to be reclaimed for human use.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Rahab the prostitute, her father's household, and all who belonged to her were saved — &ldquo;she has lived in Israel to this day&rdquo; is the formulaic phrase signaling continuing presence and integration. The <em>cherem</em> exception for Rahab is theologically significant: the ban is not ethnic (not &ldquo;all Canaanites must die&rdquo;) but theological (all who are given to YHWH's enemies must die; all who align with YHWH's purposes may live). Rahab is the narrative proof that the <em>cherem</em> is not genocide but judgment — distinguishing those who resist YHWH from those who submit. Matthew 1:5 places Rahab in the Davidic/Messianic genealogy, and Hebrews 11:31 and James 2:25 cite her as a model of faith, making the &ldquo;Gentile prostitute saved from cherem&rdquo; one of the Bible's central illustrations of grace operating outside ethnic covenant membership.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Joshua's curse in verse 26 is reported as a public declaration, and verse 26 closes with &ldquo;so YHWH was with Joshua, and his fame was in all the land.&rdquo; The curse functions as a prophetic word: Joshua speaks and YHWH fulfills (cf. 1 Kings 16:34). The <em>tikvah</em> (hope/cord) wordplay from Rahab's scarlet thread finds its shadow here in the cursed city: the city of the scarlet cord's hope is placed under a rebuilding ban so that no one can mistake Jericho for a permanent human achievement. The contrast between the saved household and the cursed ruins is the theological summary of the chapter: YHWH saves the faithful and destroys the resistant, and his word — whether of salvation or judgment — does not fail.</p>",
    "27": "<p>YHWH was with Joshua and his fame (<em>shim'o</em>, his report/reputation) spread throughout all the land. This verse functions as a summary acclamation after the first major military-theological event. The spread of Joshua's fame is not ego-building but missional: Rahab had reported in chapter 2 that &ldquo;all the inhabitants of the land melt before you,&rdquo; and the Jericho event confirms that report throughout Canaan. The fear of YHWH — mediated through the fame of his servant — is itself a mode of conquest: it breaks the morale of the remaining cities before a single additional battle. This prepares the reader for the Gibeonite deception in chapter 9, where fear of YHWH's reputation drives the deception.</p>"
  },
  "7": {
    "1": "<p>The <em>ma'al</em> (breach of faith) of the <em>cherem</em> by Achan immediately follows the Jericho triumph. <em>Ma'al</em> is a technical legal term for a breach of faith regarding sacred or dedicated things — it appears in the priestly legislation for inadvertent violations of sacred property (Lev 5:15: <em>ma'al bim'al baqodesh</em>) and in Numbers 5:6-7 for deceptive acts against another person as acts against YHWH. The term establishes from the outset that Achan's theft is not merely a personal crime but a covenant violation against YHWH himself. The genealogy — Achan son of Carmi, son of Zabdi, son of Zerah, of the tribe of Judah — connects to Zerah, Judah's son by Tamar, whose birth involved a scarlet thread (<em>shani</em>, Gen 38:28-30). The Zerah-scarlet thread connection creates a subtle irony: the tribe of the scarlet-thread birth is now the tribe that violates the <em>cherem</em> through hidden goods, reversing the Rahab pattern (the outsider who honored the scarlet thread is saved; the insider who violates the <em>cherem</em> is destroyed).</p>",
    "2": "<p>Ai (meaning &ldquo;the ruin&rdquo; in Hebrew) is identified archaeologically with some debate. The traditional identification with et-Tell, a large mound about 10 miles north of Jericho, is problematic because et-Tell shows no significant Late Bronze Age occupation — the same problem as Jericho. Alternative identifications include Khirbet el-Maqatir (proposed by Bryant Wood and others), a smaller site nearby with Late Bronze I occupation and a destruction layer consistent with the conquest period. The narrative describes Ai as a small city requiring only two to three thousand men — consistent with a minor site rather than a major urban center. The name &ldquo;Ai&rdquo; itself is significant: the city of the <em>cherem</em>-violation is called &ldquo;the ruin,&rdquo; and it will remain a tel olam (permanent ruin) after the second campaign (8:28).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The spies&rsquo; report — &ldquo;do not send all the people; about two or three thousand men are enough&rdquo; — reflects the confidence of Jericho's aftermath. But this confidence is immediately contextualized as failure to inquire of YHWH (verse 6-9 makes clear Joshua did not seek divine guidance before this reconnaissance). The military assessment is accurate (Ai is small) but the theological premise is wrong: Israel is carrying <em>cherem</em> contamination, and no military calculation can account for that. The failed battle at Ai is the narrative enactment of the principle that military strength is irrelevant when covenantal purity is compromised.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The defeat — thirty-six killed, the rest fleeing before Ai — is described with ironic reversal: &ldquo;the hearts of the people melted and became like water.&rdquo; This is the exact language used of the Canaanites&rsquo; terror before Israel (2:11; 5:1: &ldquo;their hearts melted, and there was no longer any spirit in them because of Israel&rdquo;). Now Israel's heart melts before a small Canaanite city. The <em>cherem</em> contamination has transferred Israel's status: instead of being the terrifying holy-war people of YHWH, they have become, in effect, the contaminated enemy. The theological inversion is the narrative's most pointed commentary on what sin does to the covenant people.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The flight &ldquo;before the men of Ai&rdquo; and the description of the descent as &ldquo;Shebarim&rdquo; (meaning &ldquo;breaks&rdquo; or &ldquo;quarrying pits&rdquo;) amplifies the shame of the defeat. Thirty-six deaths is a small number militarily but catastrophically significant theologically — it is the first Israelite combat death in Canaan. The pursuit &ldquo;before the gate as far as Shebarim&rdquo; inverts the typical holy-war pursuit formula (usually Israel pursuing Canaanites from the battlefield; here Canaanites pursue Israel). The narrative signals a total reversal of the divinely ordained order.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Joshua's mourning posture — tearing his clothes, falling on his face before the ark, putting dust on his head, remaining prostrate until evening — is the full ANE mourning and intercession posture (cf. David at the death of Bathsheba's child, 2 Sam 12:16). The elders of Israel join him. The posture is specifically before the ark — Joshua brings the defeat before YHWH's presence, understanding it as a theological problem, not merely a military setback. This is the proper response to holy-war defeat: not tactical reassessment but covenantal lament before the divine presence.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Joshua's lament — &ldquo;Alas, O Lord YHWH, why have you brought this people over the Jordan at all, to give us into the hands of the Amorites, to destroy us?&rdquo; — echoes Moses&rsquo;s intercession after the golden calf (Exod 32:11-12) and after the ten spies&rsquo; bad report (Num 14:13-16). The rhetorical question &ldquo;why did you bring us here only to deliver us to the enemy?&rdquo; is the standard structure of the community lament. Joshua invokes the reputation argument: if Israel is destroyed, what will the nations conclude about YHWH? The lament is itself a form of intercession — it appeals to YHWH's own stake in Israel's survival.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The completion of Joshua's lament — &ldquo;Israel has turned their backs before their enemies&rdquo; — uses the idiom &ldquo;turned the neck&rdquo; (<em>hafkhu oref</em>), the same term used for the shame of military flight. The neck turned to the enemy is the opposite of the face turned toward YHWH; it implies both military defeat and spiritual turning away. Joshua's prayer correctly identifies the theological nature of the problem without yet knowing its specific cause — the lament is the proper precursor to the divine diagnosis that follows.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The reputation argument — &ldquo;what will you do for your great name?&rdquo; — is the strongest form of intercession in the OT covenantal vocabulary. Moses used it at the golden calf (Exod 32:12), and it appears in prophetic intercession throughout (cf. Ps 79:9; Isa 48:9-11; Ezek 36:22-23). The argument is theologically profound: YHWH's name (his character and reputation) is bound up with Israel's fate because Israel is the people who bear his name. If Israel is destroyed, YHWH's reliability as a covenant God is called into question among the nations. Joshua's intercession correctly identifies that YHWH has a stake in Israel's survival that transcends Israel's own merit.</p>",
    "10": "<p>YHWH's response — &ldquo;Get up! Why have you fallen on your face? Israel has sinned&rdquo; — is abrupt and diagnostic. The time for mourning is over; the cause of the defeat is known and must be addressed. YHWH's diagnosis cuts through Joshua's confusion: the military defeat is not an anomaly requiring divine explanation; it is the predictable consequence of the <em>cherem</em> violation. The instruction to get up parallels the post-failure restoration of Israel throughout the Judges period — YHWH's response to covenantal failure is not abandonment but confrontation and restoration.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The full catalogue of Achan's sin — &ldquo;they have transgressed my covenant that I commanded them; they have taken some of the devoted things; they have stolen and lied and put them among their own belongings&rdquo; — names four distinct violations: covenant transgression, <em>cherem</em> violation, theft, and deception. The corporate framing (&ldquo;Israel has sinned... they have...&rdquo;) treats the clan-tribe-nation as a single covenant entity; Achan's individual act implicates the whole people because the covenant is corporate. This corporate liability is central to the OT covenant structure and is the theological basis for the corporate punishment that follows.</p>",
    "12": "<p>YHWH's declaration — &ldquo;I will be with you no more, unless you destroy the devoted things from among you&rdquo; — frames the <em>cherem</em> contamination as negating divine presence. The divine withdrawal is the opposite of the conquest promise (&ldquo;I will be with you as I was with Moses,&rdquo; 1:5). The condition for restoration is purging the <em>cherem</em> — not a military solution but a covenantal one. YHWH's presence in the camp is incompatible with <em>cherem</em> material because the <em>cherem</em> belongs to YHWH (it is his ban), and having it in human possession constitutes a claim on what belongs to him.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The command to consecrate the people before the lot-casting echoes the consecration before the Jordan crossing (3:5: &ldquo;Consecrate yourselves, for tomorrow YHWH will do wonders among you&rdquo;) and before Sinai (Exod 19:10-11). The ritual consecration signals that what follows is a sacred act — the lot-casting is a form of sacred discernment, possibly the Urim and Thummim (cf. 1 Sam 14:41-42 where Saul uses the lot/Urim to identify Jonathan), by which YHWH makes his knowledge visible to the community. The consecration protocol transforms the identification process from an investigation into a theophanic act.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The four-level lot process — tribe, then clan, then household, then man — is the standard narrowing structure for sacred identification procedures in the OT (cf. 1 Sam 10:20-21 where Saul is identified as king by the same tribe-clan-family-man sequence). The process is deliberate and public: each level of identification is a divine disclosure that involves the entire community, ensuring that the identification is covenantally witnessed. No accusation is made; YHWH identifies. This protects against false accusation and establishes the divine authority of the verdict.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The declared penalty for the <em>cherem</em> violator and &ldquo;all that he has&rdquo; — burning with fire — is the <em>cherem</em> penalty applied to the violator himself. The one who took the <em>cherem</em> becomes the <em>cherem</em>: the contamination transfers to the violator and must be burned as the <em>cherem</em> city was burned. This is the internal logic of the <em>cherem</em> system: anything that comes into contact with the devoted-to-destruction material shares its status. The phrase &ldquo;because he has transgressed the covenant of YHWH and because he has done a disgraceful thing in Israel&rdquo; (<em>nevalah be-Yisra'el</em>) — <em>nevalah</em> is the technical term for a sacrilegious act that violates the social-covenant order.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The lot falls on the tribe of Judah first — significant in that Judah is the royal tribe, the tribe from which David and the Messianic line will come. The identification of the violator within Judah creates a narrative tension that the book of Judges will amplify: the leading tribe is also capable of the most catastrophic covenant violation. The lot process in verses 16-18 is narrated at a pace that creates suspense — the reader knows (from verse 1) that it is Achan, but the narrative enacts the divine disclosure step by step, making the community witness each narrowing.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The lot narrows through Judah's clans to the clan of the Zerahites. The Zerahite connection to Genesis 38 (Perez and Zerah, Judah's twin sons by Tamar, with the scarlet-thread birth narrative) is the intertextual backdrop. The tribe of the scarlet thread, which should have been among the most sensitive to the significance of Rahab's scarlet cord and the covenant-marking function of that sign, is the tribe in which the <em>cherem</em> violation is hidden. The irony is not accidental: the tribe of the covenant-marking birth is now the tribe of the covenant violation.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Achan son of Carmi is identified. The name Achan (<em>'Akhan</em>) is related to the root <em>'kr</em> (to trouble/disturb), anticipating Joshua's wordplay in verse 25: &ldquo;Why did you bring trouble upon us? YHWH brings trouble upon you today.&rdquo; The <em>'Emek Achor</em> (Valley of Achor/Trouble) perpetuates the name. The genealogy — son of Carmi, son of Zabdi, son of Zerah — explicitly names the Zerah connection at the end, confirming the intertextual echo that has been building through the lot process.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Joshua's address to Achan — &ldquo;My son, give glory to YHWH God of Israel and give praise to him; tell me now what you have done; do not hide it from me&rdquo; — is a formal confession-elicitation formula. The call to &ldquo;give glory&rdquo; (<em>sim kavod</em>) before confessing is a legal-covenantal idiom that appears in John 9:24 (&ldquo;Give glory to God&rdquo; said to the man born blind, meaning &ldquo;tell the truth&rdquo;). The instruction to &ldquo;give praise&rdquo; (<em>ten lo todah</em>) — literally &ldquo;give him thanksgiving/acknowledgment&rdquo; — frames the confession as an act of worship: acknowledging YHWH's omniscience and justice by making what was hidden visible. The gentleness of &ldquo;my son&rdquo; (<em>beni</em>) makes Achan's preceding silence and the community's suffering even more pointed.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Achan's confession is immediate and complete: &ldquo;Truly (<em>amenam</em>), I have sinned against YHWH God of Israel, and this is what I did.&rdquo; The adverb <em>amenam</em> (&ldquo;truly indeed&rdquo;) is the strong affirmative — not merely acknowledgment but solemn admission. The confession precedes the description, establishing guilt before the evidence is produced. This is the proper structure of legal confession in the biblical system: verbal acknowledgment before material disclosure.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Achan describes the sequence of his sin: &ldquo;I saw... then I coveted them... and I took them.&rdquo; This is the exact sequence of Genesis 3:6 — Eve &ldquo;saw that the tree was good for food... and she took of its fruit.&rdquo; The correspondence is not incidental: the same sin-sequence (seeing, coveting, taking) that expelled humanity from the garden is the sin-sequence that violates the <em>cherem</em> and causes defeat in the land of promise. The Babylonian garment (<em>aderet shin'ar</em>) is significant: <em>Shin'ar</em> is the Hebrew name for Babylon (cf. Gen 11:2, the Tower of Babel narrative; Dan 1:2, where the temple vessels are taken to the land of Shinar/Babylon). The coveted item is literally a piece of the anti-kingdom — and the two hundred shekels of silver (the price of a slave, cf. Gen 37:28 where Joseph is sold for twenty) and the fifty-shekel gold bar complete the financial calculation of the theft. The verb <em>chamad</em> (coveted) is the exact verb of the tenth commandment (Exod 20:17: &ldquo;you shall not covet [<em>lo tachmod</em>]&rdquo;), making Achan's sin a direct violation of the Decalogue as well as the <em>cherem</em> command.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The messengers run (<em>ratzim</em>) to the tent and find the items hidden exactly where Achan described — confirming the truthfulness of his confession and the completeness of the divine disclosure. The items are brought to Joshua and all Israel, laid before YHWH. The public display before the covenant community is required: this is not a private judicial matter but a covenantal violation that affected the whole people and whose resolution must be communally witnessed.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The goods are &ldquo;spread out before YHWH&rdquo; — the same phrase used for laying offerings before the divine presence. The <em>cherem</em> material is finally in its proper location before YHWH, though through a path of sin rather than devotion. The spreading out before YHWH is the preliminary to the community's verdict, which YHWH's prior lot-identification has already determined. The human judicial process confirms what YHWH disclosed; it does not make an independent judgment.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Joshua and all Israel take Achan, his sons and daughters, his oxen and donkeys and sheep, his tent, and all he has, and bring them to the Valley of Achor. The corporate punishment extending to Achan's children has disturbed commentators throughout history (cf. Deut 24:16: &ldquo;Fathers shall not be put to death because of their children, nor shall children be put to death because of their fathers&rdquo;). The rabbinical tradition (Mishnah Sanhedrin 6:2) ruled that the children were brought only to witness, not executed — though verse 25 can be read as including them. The corporate nature of the punishment reflects the <em>cherem</em>-contamination logic: everything associated with the violation is treated as <em>cherem</em>, as YHWH warned in 6:18. The Valley of Achor is identified in the Buqeiah valley southwest of Jericho, a relatively isolated location that would later acquire positive covenant significance in Hosea 2:15 (&ldquo;I will give her the Valley of Achor as a door of hope&rdquo;).</p>",
    "25": "<p>Joshua's words — &ldquo;Why did you bring trouble (<em>akharttanu</em>) upon us? YHWH brings trouble upon you today (<em>ye'akhorcha</em>)&rdquo; — are the explicit etymology of both the name Achan and the Valley of Achor. The wordplay is the narrative's theological verdict in condensed form: the one who brought trouble receives trouble; the agent of <em>cherem</em>-violation becomes the object of <em>cherem</em>-execution. All Israel stoned him with stones and burned them with fire after stoning — combining the execution for capital crimes (stoning, Deut 17:5-7) with the <em>cherem</em> fire-destruction (6:24). The double execution confirms that Achan's status has been transformed: he is now the <em>cherem</em> object that must be burned.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The great heap of stones raised over Achan echoes the heap raised over the king of Ai (8:29) and creates a geographical memorial of covenant judgment. The Valley of Achor as a place-name perpetuates the event in Israel's geography. The formulaic close — &ldquo;Then YHWH turned from his burning anger&rdquo; — uses the same language as the turning of divine anger after covenant atonement (Num 25:11, Phinehas's act turning away YHWH's anger; Exod 32:12, Moses's intercession). The restoration of divine favor follows the complete execution of the <em>cherem</em> principle: contamination removed, covenant order restored, holy war can resume. The chapter closes with Israel in the same position as after the Jordan crossing — clean before YHWH, ready for the next campaign.</p>"
  },
  "8": {
    "1": "<p>YHWH's renewed command — &ldquo;Do not fear and do not be dismayed&rdquo; — is the <em>al tira</em> formula of holy war (cf. 1:9; 10:8, 25; 11:6), always spoken before a divinely sanctioned battle. Its repetition after the Achan episode signals that the covenant breach has been resolved and the divine warrior has re-engaged with Israel. The command is theologically load-bearing: YHWH is restoring the holy-war promise that was suspended during the <em>cherem</em> violation period. The military strategy that follows — the ambush — is given by YHWH directly, marking it as divinely sanctioned rather than merely humanly devised.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The explicit permission for Israel to take the spoil and livestock of Ai — &ldquo;only its spoil and its livestock you shall take as plunder for yourselves&rdquo; — deliberately contrasts with Jericho's total <em>cherem</em>. Ai is not a firstfruits city; it is not under the same absolute ban. The permission signals that the Jericho <em>cherem</em> was the unique firstfruits principle, not a standing rule for all conquered cities. This distinction will become explicit in Deuteronomy 20, which distinguishes between Canaanite cities within the land (total <em>cherem</em>) and distant cities (permissible spoil); Ai's treatment suggests that even within Canaan the firstfruits rule applied only to Jericho as the first city. The tactical instruction to set an ambush mirrors what will become a standard Hebrew warfare technique (cf. the Benjaminite ambush at Gibeah, Judg 20:29-36).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The thirty thousand mighty men of valor sent for the night ambush reflects careful planning: the ambush force must be in position before dawn without alerting Ai's defenders. The number thirty thousand for a city requiring only two to three thousand for the direct assault (7:3) seems large for a flanking force — some manuscripts and the parallel in 8:12 give five thousand. The discrepancy may reflect two different forces (a larger force for the initial night movement, a smaller advance ambush party; both present in the narrative at vv. 9 and 12). The complexity of the operation — a main force, an ambush force, coordinated night movement, and a feigned retreat — demonstrates advanced tactical capability for the period.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The ambush instructions — &ldquo;you shall not go very far from the city; all of you be ready&rdquo; — emphasize close positioning. The ambush works by the main force's feigned retreat drawing out the entire garrison of Ai, leaving the city empty and vulnerable to the ambush party's attack from behind. The tactical logic depends on Ai's overconfidence after the first Israelite defeat (7:5): the men of Ai &ldquo;did not know there was an ambush against them behind the city&rdquo; (8:14) because the previous encounter had established a pattern of Israeli weakness. YHWH uses Ai's overconfidence — itself the fruit of Israel's previous sin and defeat — as the mechanism of their destruction.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The feigned retreat strategy — &ldquo;I and all the people who are with me will approach the city; and when they come out against us as before, we will flee from them&rdquo; — exploits the memory of the first battle. The men of Ai will pursue based on the pattern of 7:5; they will not expect that this flight is tactical rather than genuine. The phrase &ldquo;as before&rdquo; (<em>kebar'ishona</em>) is the key: Joshua is using the enemy's knowledge of the previous battle as the instrument of their defeat. The tactical brilliance is divine — given by YHWH (v. 2) — and operates through the enemy's own confidence and memory.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The anticipated enemy reasoning — &ldquo;they are fleeing from us, as before&rdquo; — will cause them to pursue and leave the city empty. The phrase &ldquo;as before&rdquo; appears again, confirming that the first defeat is being deliberately used as bait. This double use of Israel's humiliation as the mechanism of Ai's defeat is a characteristic pattern of the OT's theology of reversal: the weakness of God's people becomes the instrument of the enemy's undoing (cf. 1 Cor 1:27-28).</p>",
    "7": "<p>The ambush party's trigger — rising from their position and seizing the city when Joshua's party flees — is the hinge of the entire strategy. The party must wait for the garrison to fully exit before moving; premature action would alert the defenders and allow some to return. The instruction &ldquo;YHWH your God will give it into your hand&rdquo; frames the tactical waiting as covenantal trust: the ambush party waits on YHWH's timing, not on their own judgment of the right moment.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The command to set the city on fire when they seize it creates a visible signal — the smoke column of 8:20 — that will stop the pursuing army of Ai by revealing that their city is taken and burning behind them. The fire is both the execution of the <em>cherem</em> (Ai is also devoted to destruction) and the tactical signal that triggers the main force's reversal. YHWH's instructions are simultaneously theological (the city must be burned as devoted) and tactical (the smoke signals the ambush success). The integration of the covenantal and military dimensions is characteristic of Joshua's holy-war narrative.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Joshua spends the night in the valley — the main force encamped in the open, vulnerable but trusting in YHWH's plan. The overnight stay before the ambush force moves into position creates a night of waiting that parallels the Passover night and the Jordan-crossing night. The narrative's repeated references to night, early morning, dawn, and the sequence of the day emphasize that the conquest operates on YHWH's timing: everything happens at the appointed moment, not through human impatience.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Joshua rose early in the morning, mustered the people, and went up to Ai with the elders of Israel before the people. The mustering before dawn is the standard holy-war preparation — the army assembled and ready before light. The presence of the elders of Israel in the advance party elevates this from a military engagement to a covenantal act: the leadership of the covenant community is present as witnesses of YHWH's fulfillment of the battle-promise.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The main force positions north of Ai with a valley between them and the city. The geographical details — north of Ai, valley to the west where the ambush party waits — are consistent with the terrain around et-Tell and Khirbet el-Maqatir (both proposed sites). The careful positioning also ensures that Joshua's main force is visible to Ai from the city walls, making the feigned retreat credible: the Ai garrison can watch Israel approach from the north and choose to sortie against them.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The five thousand of the ambush party are positioned between Bethel and Ai, on Ai's west side. The mention of Bethel as a reference point is significant: Bethel (Luz) is immediately adjacent to Ai in the narrative geography, and the Bethel garrison will also try to intervene in the battle (8:17: &ldquo;there was not a man left in Ai or Bethel who had not gone out after Israel&rdquo;). The ambush's position between the two cities neutralizes both simultaneously: when Ai and Bethel both commit their forces to the pursuit, both cities are left undefended.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The main army to the north, the ambush to the west: the tactical pincer is set. The Hebrew word for the &ldquo;rear guard&rdquo; here is <em>ekev</em>, related to &ldquo;heel&rdquo; — the same root as Jacob&rsquo;s name (<em>Ya'akov</em>, from <em>ekev</em>, heel-grabber). The heel that grabs from behind is both the patriarchal echo and the tactical image: the ambush force is Israel's &ldquo;heel,&rdquo; the unexpected grabber from the rear. Joshua went into the valley that night — the repeated detail of Joshua's position in the valley emphasizes his accessibility to the troops and his personal leadership of the frontal engagement.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The king of Ai, seeing Israel, hurried and went out early to meet them in battle. The king's response — immediate, personal, confident — reflects the overconfidence set up by the first battle's victory. He leads his entire force in the pursuit, abandoning any garrison defense. The narrator notes &ldquo;he did not know there was an ambush against him behind the city,&rdquo; a tragic irony: the information the king lacks is precisely what makes his confident advance fatal.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Joshua and all Israel pretended to be beaten before them and fled by the way of the wilderness — the feigned retreat. The phrase &ldquo;pretended to be beaten&rdquo; (<em>vayyinagu liphnehem</em>, literally &ldquo;were made to flee before them&rdquo;) could describe genuine or feigned flight; the context makes clear it is intentional. The direction &ldquo;by the way of the wilderness&rdquo; draws the pursuit away from the city and toward the ambush zone, extending the pursuing force's vulnerability.</p>",
    "16": "<p>All the people of Ai are called out to pursue — the total mobilization leaves the city completely empty. The phrase &ldquo;all the people who were in Ai&rdquo; including those of Bethel emphasizes the totality of the trap. The city is not merely under-garrisoned; it is completely evacuated. This total evacuation is the precondition for the ambush party to take and burn the city without resistance.</p>",
    "17": "<p>There was not a man left in Ai or Bethel who had not gone out after Israel. The pairing of Ai and Bethel reflects the military alliance between the two cities. Bethel (the city of the patriarch Jacob&rsquo;s dream, Gen 28:10-22) will later be condemned in the divided monarchy as the site of Jeroboam's golden calves (1 Kings 12:29). The narrative briefly mentions Bethel here without elaboration, but the detail that Bethel's garrison also abandons its city in the pursuit establishes the scope of Israel's victory as extending to the broader region.</p>",
    "18": "<p>YHWH says to Joshua: &ldquo;Stretch out the javelin [<em>kidon</em>] in your hand toward Ai, for I will give it into your hand.&rdquo; Joshua stretches out the javelin and does not draw it back until the destruction is complete (v. 26). This is the explicit Moses-echo of the chapter: Moses stretched out his staff/rod over the Reed Sea (Exod 14:16, 21) and held it up through the Amalek battle (Exod 17:11-12, &ldquo;whenever Moses held up his hand, Israel prevailed&rdquo;) — Joshua&rsquo;s extended javelin is the conquest-phase version of the same extended-staff symbol. The divine presence that acts through Moses&rsquo;s extended rod acts through Joshua&rsquo;s extended javelin; the battle is YHWH&rsquo;s by the signal of the leader&rsquo;s raised hand/weapon, not by the army&rsquo;s military effort.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The ambush party rises immediately when Joshua stretches out the javelin, enters the city, and sets it on fire. The rapid sequence — &ldquo;arose quickly from their place and ran&rdquo; — emphasizes the timing: the ambush party has been watching Joshua's signal, ready to move the instant it is given. The coordination between the main force's signal and the ambush force's action is the military-theological unity of the chapter: one command from the divine warrior mediated through Joshua activates the entire strategy simultaneously.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The men of Ai look back and see the smoke of the city going up to the heavens — and have no place to flee, for Israel turned to face those who pursued them. The smoke column is both the signal of the ambush's success and the demoralizing news that cuts off the pursuing army. The city they left to pursue Israel is burning behind them; the army they were pursuing has reversed and is now facing them. The trap closes. The phrase &ldquo;the smoke of the city went up to heaven&rdquo; echoes the smoke of Sodom (Gen 19:28) — the smoke of divine judgment ascending.</p>",
    "21": "<p>When Joshua and all Israel saw that the ambush had taken the city and the smoke went up, they turned back and struck down the men of Ai. The visual signal — the smoke column — coordinates the two-front attack. The frontal force, which had been fleeing, reverses and attacks; the ambush force, which has taken the city, emerges to attack from the rear. The men of Ai are caught between two attacking forces with no city to retreat to. The tactical coordination is the enacted form of the holy-war theology: YHWH's plan, executed by obedient Israel, produces the victory.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The men in the ambush also came out of the city against them, so they were in the middle of Israel, some on this side and some on that side. No survivors or refugees — the force that pursued Israel is surrounded and destroyed completely. The encirclement is total: the <em>cherem</em> city of Ai suffers the same fate as Jericho, but through tactical means rather than liturgical procession. YHWH's methods vary; his covenant requirements are consistent.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The king of Ai was taken alive and brought to Joshua. The taking of the king alive while all his forces are killed is consistent with the ANE conquest formula: the king is brought to the victorious king for public humiliation and execution (cf. the five kings displayed and executed in 10:24-26). The king&rsquo;s capture is the symbolic completion of the military victory — not only is the city taken, but its ruler is in Israelite hands, demonstrating the total defeat of Ai&rsquo;s sovereignty.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The total destruction of all the inhabitants of Ai in the open wilderness where Israel pursued them — twelve thousand, all the people of Ai — completes the <em>cherem</em>. The number twelve thousand is specific enough to suggest a census basis. The slaughter in the open field rather than in the city reflects the success of the ambush strategy: the entire military force was drawn out into the open where they could not use the city's defenses. The <em>cherem</em> of Ai's inhabitants was the divine sentence; the tactical plan was the means of executing it in a way that minimized Israelite casualties.</p>",
    "25": "<p>All who fell that day, both men and women, were twelve thousand, all the people of Ai. The explicit inclusion of women in the count is consistent with the <em>cherem</em> requirement (6:21: &ldquo;men and women, young and old&rdquo;). The total population count for a city confirms Ai's status as a small settlement (compared to Jericho, the &ldquo;great city,&rdquo; 10:2) — consistent with the &ldquo;two to three thousand&rdquo; assessment of the first spies&rsquo; report and the proposed identification with Khirbet el-Maqatir or a similar minor site.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Joshua did not draw back his hand with which he stretched out the javelin until he had devoted all the inhabitants of Ai to destruction. The sustained extension of the javelin through the entire battle is the full enactment of the Moses-Amalek parallel (Exod 17:11-12: &ldquo;as long as Moses held up his hand, Israel prevailed&rdquo;). Unlike the Amalek battle, where Moses required Aaron and Hur to hold up his arms, Joshua sustains the javelin himself through the complete destruction — suggesting a typological progression: the sign of divine agency through the leader's raised hand is now carried by Joshua without assistance, anticipating the greater Joshua who will complete what Moses began.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Israel took the livestock and the spoil of the city as plunder for themselves, according to YHWH's word which he commanded Joshua. The explicit note that the spoil-taking was &ldquo;according to the word of YHWH&rdquo; (v. 2) distinguishes Ai's treatment from Jericho's: Jericho's total <em>cherem</em> was the firstfruits offering; Ai's permitted spoil is the reward of the subsequent conquest. The distinction is theologically important for later readers: the <em>cherem</em> was not a standing rule against all war-spoil but a specific firstfruits command applying to Jericho.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Joshua burned Ai and made it a <em>tel olam</em> — a permanent ruin heap. <em>Tel</em> is the Hebrew/Aramaic term for a mound of layered ruins, which is the origin of the modern archaeological term &ldquo;tell&rdquo; or &ldquo;tel&rdquo; for the artificial mounds of ancient Near Eastern sites formed by successive occupations. A <em>tel olam</em> is a mound made desolate forever, uninhabited. The irony of the name &ldquo;Ai&rdquo; (&ldquo;the ruin&rdquo;) is completed: the city already named &ldquo;ruin&rdquo; is made into the archetypal ruin — a permanent monument to YHWH's covenant judgment. The archaeological site identification debate (et-Tell vs. Khirbet el-Maqatir) hinges in part on which site shows no subsequent occupation — consistent with the <em>tel olam</em> designation.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The king of Ai was hanged on a tree until evening — then at sunset Joshua commanded that they take his body down, throw it at the entrance of the gate, and raise over it a great heap of stones. The hanging of the king invokes Deuteronomy 21:22-23: &ldquo;if a man has committed a crime punishable by death and he is put to death, and you hang him on a tree, his body shall not remain all night on the tree, but you shall bury him the same day, for a hanged man is cursed by God.&rdquo; Joshua follows this law precisely — the king is hung until evening and removed at sunset. The king of Ai bears the curse of God in his public hanging; the stone heap over his body at the city gate makes him a permanent warning monument, the anti-type of the stone memorial at Gilgal (4:20-24). The two stone memorials — one of salvation (Gilgal), one of judgment (Ai's gate) — frame Israel's entry into the land.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Then Joshua built an altar to YHWH, the God of Israel, on Mount Ebal. The immediate transition from the conquest of Ai to the Ebal covenant ceremony is theologically deliberate: the conquest is not primarily a military campaign but a covenant enactment. Mount Ebal (elevation 940m) and Mount Gerizim (elevation 881m) are the two peaks flanking the Shechem valley in central Canaan — the geographical center of the land. The Ebal ceremony fulfills Moses&rsquo;s command in Deuteronomy 27:4-8 to build a stone altar on Ebal immediately upon entering the land. Shechem is also the site of Abraham&rsquo;s first altar in Canaan (Gen 12:6-7) and Jacob&rsquo;s purchase of land (Gen 33:18-20) — the covenant ceremony happens at the patriarchal center of the land-promise.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The altar specifications — uncut stones, no iron tool used — follow Exodus 20:25 and Deuteronomy 27:5-6 exactly. The prohibition on dressed stone for altars reflects the principle that human craftsmanship should not enhance what is offered to YHWH; the altar&rsquo;s roughness is its fitness. The offering of burnt offerings and peace offerings on the altar transitions from military action to covenant worship: having secured central Canaan through the Ai campaign, Israel pauses at the land&rsquo;s patriarchal center to reaffirm the covenant relationship that grounds the entire conquest.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Joshua wrote on the stones a copy of the law of Moses — the Torah inscription on plastered stones fulfills Deuteronomy 27:3, 8 (&ldquo;write on the stones all the words of this law&rdquo;). This is the covenant-boundary-marker inscription technique known from ANE treaty texts: the Hittite suzerainty treaties required that the treaty text be set up publicly and read periodically. The Torah-on-stones at Ebal is Israel&rsquo;s equivalent: the covenant terms inscribed in stone at the land&rsquo;s center, visible to all, establishing that the land is held under covenant obligation. The Samaritan Pentateuch has a variant reading in Deuteronomy 27:4 specifying Gerizim rather than Ebal as the altar site — a textual variant reflecting the later Samaritan-Judean conflict over the proper site of worship, but the MT is consistent in specifying Ebal for the altar.</p>",
    "33": "<p>All Israel — elders, officers, judges, ark of the covenant, Levitical priests, native Israelites and sojourners (<em>gerim</em>) — stood on both sides of the ark before the Levitical priests, half facing Mount Gerizim and half facing Mount Ebal. The inclusion of the <em>gerim</em> (resident aliens/sojourners) in the covenant assembly at Ebal is among the most significant details in the chapter. The <em>gerim</em> are present in the land&rsquo;s first formal covenant ceremony — not as observers but as participants in the covenant blessings and curses. This establishes from Israel&rsquo;s first act in the land that the covenant community is not ethnically restricted: those who dwell among YHWH&rsquo;s people under covenant obligation are included in the covenant assembly. Rahab&rsquo;s household (ch. 6) and the Gibeonites (ch. 9) will develop this principle narratively.</p>",
    "34": "<p>Joshua read aloud all the words of the law, the blessing and the curse, according to all that is written in the Book of the Law — the public Torah reading at Ebal is the covenant ceremony from Deuteronomy 31:10-13 enacted at the land&rsquo;s first assembly. Deuteronomy commanded that the Torah be read every seven years at the Feast of Booths; Joshua performs the first public Torah reading in the land before the seven-year cycle even begins, establishing the precedent at the land&rsquo;s inaugural moment. The later parallel is Nehemiah 8, where Ezra reads the Torah at the Water Gate after the return from exile — the post-exilic covenant renewal is explicitly patterned on this Ebal ceremony as the inaugural covenant constitution of Israel in the land.</p>",
    "35": "<p>There was not a word of all that Moses commanded that Joshua did not read before all the assembly of Israel, and the women and the little ones and the sojourners (<em>gerim</em>) who lived among them. The completeness formula — &ldquo;not a word of all that Moses commanded&rdquo; — anticipates the completeness formula of 21:45 and 23:14 (&ldquo;not one word has failed of all the good things that YHWH your God promised&rdquo;). Joshua&rsquo;s complete reading of the Torah is the covenantal counterpart to YHWH&rsquo;s complete fulfillment of his promises: both acts are total, without remainder. The double mention of women, little ones, and <em>gerim</em> (both in verse 33 and here) underscores the radical inclusivity of the Ebal covenant assembly — the covenant constitution of Israel in the land is heard and entered into by all who dwell in the community, regardless of gender, age, or ethnic origin.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-context', 'joshua')
    merge_comm(c, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'joshua', c)
    print('joshua ch 6-8: context written')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
